## Part 3 – Shellshock Vulnerability Analysis

Building on the previous network design and protocol analysis, the following section explores a real-world vulnerability scenario and incident response within the WBMUD network.

Shellshock is a critical vulnerability found in the Bash shell, allowing attackers to execute malicious commands remotely by exploiting environment variables.

In this lab scenario, the attacker node in the DMZ could exploit this vulnerability to gain access to the OT web server and potentially move laterally within the network.

---

## Part 4 – Incident Response

### Attack Path
The attack begins from the DMZ attacker node and targets the OT web server. After compromising the server, the attacker can move laterally within the network.

### Root Cause
The attack was caused by an unpatched vulnerability and weak access control mechanisms.

### Remediation Plan
- Apply system patches regularly  
- Configure firewalls  
- Use HTTPS instead of HTTP  
- Use SSH instead of Telnet  
- Implement monitoring and intrusion detection  

